{"title_page": "1928 Auckland Rugby League season", "text_new": "The 1928 [[Auckland Rugby League]] season was its 19th. It was a very busy season, with ten representative fixtures including matches against the touring [[England national rugby league team|England]] team. The senior club season featured over 110 matches through various competitions and did not finish until late October when suburban cricket competitions had already begun.\n\n[[North Shore Albions|Devonport]] won the Senior A Championship for the first time under the [[North Shore Albions|Devonport]] name, though they had won it twice before as [[North Shore Albions]], prior to the merger with Sunnyside. [[Marist Saints|Marist]] won the Roope Rooster Trophy for the first time. This was their first major rugby league trophy and they also went on to defeat Devonport to win the Stormont Shield. [[Grafton Athletic rugby league team|Grafton]] won the Senior B Grade competition with an undefeated season, though they were beaten in the promotion relegation match with [[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie]]. [[Point Chevalier Pirates|Point Chevalier]] defeated [[Grafton Athletic rugby league team|Grafton]] in the Stallard Cup final which was the Senior B knockout competition. The season was notable for the number of teams which played sides from other areas. [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby]], [[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond]], [[Parnell rugby league club|Parnell]], and the [[Northcote Tigers|Northcote and Birkenhead Ramblers]] all played sides from north Auckland and the [[Waikato]].\n\nAt the annual general meeting of [[Auckland Rugby League]] it was noted that out of the 28 playing days during the 1927 season thirteen of them were played in wet weather however crowds were still good and they were happy with the growth of the game. It was also planned for further developments at [[Carlaw Park]] consisting of \u201cconveniences for ladies\u2026extra accommodation\u2026 for players, and three more dressing rooms\u201d at a cost of \u00a360. There was a lengthy discussion about [[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie's]] application to join the A Grade. They had won the B Grade competition and defeated the last placed Grafton from A Grade.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Governing Body/Report on the Past Season\n| page = 17\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19907\n| date = 1928-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280328.2.154\n| accessdate = 2019-09-29}}</ref> The annual general meeting was held at the [[Auckland Chamber of Commerce]] on Swanson Street.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Activities/Mew Officers Elected/Plans for Coming Season\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19920\n| date = 1928-04-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280413.2.165.5\n| accessdate = 2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\nThe Management Committee announced at the midway mark of the senior club season that the Thistle Cup would be awarded to the A or B grade team that had scored the most points in the second round of competition. If two teams were tied then the trophy would be awarded to the team which had scored the most points for the whole season.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Management Committee/Thistle Cup Competition\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19978\n| date = 1928-06-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280621.2.167.4\n| accessdate = 2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\n==Ground Availability==\nAn ongoing issue for many clubs in Auckland was the availability of playing fields as the number of teams grew. During the season [[Northcote Tigers|Northcote]] opened a new field at Stafford Park which is still in existence adjacent to State Highway 1 just north of the [[Auckland Harbour Bridge]]. Devonport also had a deputation present at the [[Devonport Borough Council]] meeting on 10 May to ask about the shortage of grounds in the area. The club asked for permission to use some of the spare cricket grounds for matches. The Mayor, Mr. E. Aldridge said there would be a ground available at Stanley Bay.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Devonport Borough/Shortage of Sports Areas\n| page = 12\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19943\n| date = 1928-05-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280511.2.133\n| accessdate = 2019-10-01}}</ref>\n\n==Rule Changes==\nAfter Round 5 the issue of time keeping in matches at [[Carlaw Park]] was raised at the weekly Management Committee meeting. The bell had been rung in the match between [[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond]] and Devonport at [[Carlaw Park]] before the ball was dead which was against previously arranged rules. Agreement could not be reached on whether the timekeeper or referee should be responsible for calling time. In the end it was decided that official timekeepers should attend the Referees\u2019 Association meeting for instructions.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =The Management Committee/The Calling of Time/Proposed Match for June 4\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LIX, Issue 121\n| date = 1928-05-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19280524.2.126.3\n| accessdate = 2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\nIt was noted that the dead ball area on both fields at [[Carlaw Park]] had been reduced from 12 yards to 8yards in accordance with the laws of Rugby League.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Senior Matches/Individual Scorers\u2019 List/Taylor Leads the Way\n| page = 16\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19971\n| date = 1928-06-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280613.2.177.2\n| accessdate = 2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\nA rule change came into effect during the season after the annual meeting of the [[Rugby Football League|English Rugby League]]. They decided that no forward at any time in the scrum could have both feet off the ground. Also forwards could not drop to one knee to attempt to hook the ball. The game in New Zealand would adhere to these rules.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Amendments to Scrum Laws\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19983\n| date = 1928-06-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280627.2.148.4\n| accessdate = 2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\n{{s-start}}\n        {{s-bef|before=[[1927 Auckland Rugby League season|1927]]}}\n        {{s-ttl|title=19th [[Auckland Rugby League]] season\n        |years=1928}}\n        {{s-aft|after=[[1929 Auckland Rugby League season|1929]]}}\n        {{end}}\n\n==First Grade Championship==\n===Final A Grade Standings===\n{|\n|-\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!width=175 |Team\n!width=20 abbr=\"Played\" |Pld\n!width=20 abbr=\"Won\" |W\n!width=20 abbr=\"Drawn\" |D\n!width=20 abbr=\"Lost\" |L\n!width=20 abbr=\"For\" |F\n!width=20 abbr=\"Against\" |A\n!width=20 abbr=\"Points\" |Pts\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[North Shore Albions|Devonport United]]\n|12||9||0||3||224||149||'''18'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond Rovers]]\n|12||7||1||4||143||132||'''15'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Newton Rangers]]\n|12||7||0||5||143||138||'''14'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]]\n|12||5||2||5||154||144||'''12'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Marist Saints|Marist Old Boys]]\n|12||5||1||6||154||170||'''11'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[City Rovers]]\n|12||4||0||8||144||164||'''8'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie]]\n|12||3||0||9||102||162||'''6'''\n|-\n|}\n\n===First Grade A Division Fixtures===\nThe opening weekend of the season saw 4 first grade matches played at [[Carlaw Park]], though these matches were not part of the competition. The round was dedicated to Richard Stack (commonly known as Dick Stack) of the [[Newton Rangers]] who had suffered a broken leg in the Stormont Shield final the previous season and the injury was so bad [[Auckland Hospital]] staff were forced to amputate it. This mean that he was unable to continue in his career and so the league fundraised for him to start him in his own business. \u00a3500 was taken at the gates for him. The day also featured a program of boxing matches with the prizes donated back to Stack. After all the accounts were balanced it was worked out that the fund for Stack totalled \u00a3610 12/3.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Stack Benefit/Sum of \u00a3610 for League Football Player/A Pleasing Effort\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LIX, Issue 152\n| date = 1928-06-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19280629.2.15\n| accessdate = 2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nRound 1 saw the newly promoted [[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie]] upset [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby]]. The season was ceremonially kicked off by Miss Peggy Rhodes, daughter of George Rhodes, the chairman of [[Auckland Rugby League]] Management Committee.\n\nFollowing the conclusion of the first ground of Senior A Grade matches ''[[The New Zealand Herald]]'' published for the first time the individual points tallies of all the point scorers. This was the first time this had been done. Taylor of [[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond]] led the standings with 46 points, L. Scott of [[North Shore Albions|Devonport]] had 33, while [[Craddock Dufty|Dufty]] of [[Newton Rangers|Newton]] was third with 26 points.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Senior Matches/Individual Scorers\u2019 List/Taylor Leads the Way\n| page = 16\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19971\n| date = 1928-06-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280613.2.177.2\n| accessdate = 2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\nIt was decided by [[Auckland Rugby League]] after the 3rd round that they would no longer play curtain-raiser matches by Senior A Grade teams at 1:30pm. This was due to players having difficulty getting to the ground on time as they often worked on Saturdays and had to travel from the outer suburbs. A recent example had been the [[Newton Rangers]] v [[North Shore Albions|Devonport]] match where several [[Newton Rangers|Newton]] players had arrived late and the match was so late kicking off that the second half lasted only 25 minutes instead of 40.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =The Stack Benefit Fund/Next Saturday\u2019s Attraction/Devonport and Richmond\n| page = 16\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19947\n| date = 1928-05-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280516.2.171.2\n| accessdate = 2019-10-01}}</ref>\n\nThe Round 6 match between [[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond]] and [[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie]] was played on the Kings Birthday holiday as part of the celebrations.\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | 1928 First Grade Results\n|-\n|\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | Venue\n! scope=\"col\" | Attendance\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Stack Benefit Matches\n| 21 April <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Stack Benefit Matches/Large Crowd at Carlaw Park/An Interesting Day\u2019s Sport\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19928\n| date = 1928-04-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280423.2.149.2\n| accessdate = 2019-09-30}}</ref>\n|| Ponsonby || 13 || Newton || 0 || Carlaw Park # 1||10,000\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | -\n| 21 April || Marist || 3 || Devonport || 0 || Carlaw Park # 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | -\n| 21 April || Richmond || 10 || City || 0 || Carlaw Park # 2\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | -\n| 21 April || Grafton || 2 || Ellerslie || 0 || Carlaw Park # 2\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Round 1\n| 28 April <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Opening of the Season/Two Surprise Results/Ellerslie Beats Ponsonby\n| page =13 \n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19933\n| date = 1928-03-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280430.2.152.10\n| accessdate 