url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280910.2.102\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\nThe final saw Grafton and [[Point Chevalier Pirates|Point Chevalier]] tied at the end of normal time necessitating two extra periods of five minutes before Monaghan of [[Point Chevalier Pirates|Point Chevalier]] kicked a penalty goal to win the cup. This handed [[Point Chevalier Pirates|Point Chevalier]] their first ever senior trophy.\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | 1928 Stallard Cup Results\n|-\n|\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | Venue\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Round 1\n| 8 Sep <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Roope Rooster Competition/First Series of Matches/Devonport\u2019s Narrow Victory\n| page =13\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 20047\n| date = 1928-09-10\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280910.2.132.1\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n|| Point Chevalier|| 15 || Mangere || 8 || Carlaw Park # 2, 1:45pm \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | -\n| 8 Sep || Grafton || 10 || Northcote || 2 ||  Auckland Domain # 1, 3pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | -\n| 8 Sep || Otahuhu || 5 || Kingsland || 8 || Otahuhu, 3pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Semi Final\n| 22 Sep <ref>{{cite news \n| title = Roope Rooster Competition/Play in the Semi-Final/Marist Beats Devonport\n| page =14\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 20059\n| date = 1928-09-24\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280924.2.156.1\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n|| Point Chevalier|| 13 || Parnell || 6 || Point Chevalier, 3pm \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Semi Final\n| 22 Sep <ref>{{cite news \n| title = Roope Rooster Competition/Play in the Semi-Final/Marist Beats Devonport\n| page =14\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 20059\n| date = 1928-09-24\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280924.2.156.1\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>|| Grafton|| 18 || Kingsland ||10  || Carlaw Park # 1, 1:45pm \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Final\n| 30 Sep <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Roope Rooster Competition/The Semi-Final Replay/Ponsonby Defeats Newton\n| page =14\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 20065\n| date = 1928-10-01\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19281001.2.154.1\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n|| Point Chevalier|| 15 || Grafton || 13 || Carlaw Park # 2, 3pm \n|-\n|}\n\n===Labour Day Tournament===\nThe \u2018Labour Day Tournament\u2019 was played over two days (the official holiday, and the following Saturday). [[Marist Saints|Marist]] won the trophy despite having to win two games on the first day, and two more on the second. For their efforts they were awarded \u00a350 in prize money.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Marists Victory\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LIX, Issue 256\n| date = 1928-10-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19281029.2.133.8\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | Results\n|-\n|\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | Venue\n! scope=\"col\" | Attendance\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Round 1\n| 20 Oct <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Labour Day Competition/Elimination Round Played/Finals Next Saturday\n| page = 14\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 20083\n| date = 1928-10-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19281022.2.153.2\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n|| Marist || 12 || Huntly || 10 || Carlaw Park # 1, 2pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | -\n| 20 Oct || City || 11 || Devonport || 3 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | -\n| 20 Oct || Richmond || 11 || Newton || 5 || Carlaw Park # 2, 3pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | -\n| 20 Oct || Ponsonby || 25 || Point Chevalier || 13 || Carlaw Park # 2, 4pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | -\n| 20 Oct || Marist || 11 || Ellerslie || 8 || Carlaw Park # 1, 4pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Semi Final\n| 27 Oct <ref>{{cite news \n| title = Labour Day Competition/Marist Team Successful\n| page =13\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 20089\n| date = 1928-10-29\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19281029.2.137.11\n| accessdate = 2019-10-05}}</ref>\n|| Richmond|| 11 || Ponsonby || 5 || Carlaw Park # 1, 2pm||2,500\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Semi Final\n| 27 Oct || Marist|| 17 || City || 12 || Carlaw Park # 2, 2pm \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Final\n| 27 Oct || Marist|| 12 || Richmond|| 5 || Carlaw Park # 1, 4pm \n|-\n|}\n\n==Other Club Matches and Lower Grades==\n===Lower Grade Clubs===\n<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Junior Competitions\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LIX, Issue 256\n| date = 1928-10-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19281029.2.133.8\n| accessdate = 2019-10-05}}</ref>\nGrades were made of the following teams with the winning teams in bold:\n*'''Second Grade''': Akarana, Devonport, Mangere, Newton, Northcote, Ponsonby, Remuera, Richmond (Won by Devonport who were 6 pts clear of Remuera, Ponsonby and Newton), (Newton won the knockout competition)\n*'''Third Grade Open''': Athletic, Devonport A, Devonport B, Ellerslie, Glen Eden, Kingsland, Mount Albert, New Lynn, Northcote, Otahuhu, Parnell, Ponsonby, Richmond  (Won by Richmond, 2 pts clear or Mount Albert) (Richmond won the knockout competition)\n*'''Third Grade Intermediate''': City, Devonport, New Lynn, Newton, Newmarket, Point Chevalier, Ponsonby, Remuera, Richmond (Won by Richmond, 8pts clear of Ponsonby), (Richmond won the knockout competition)\n*'''Fourth Grade''': Akarana, City, Devonport, Ellerslie, Northcote, Otahuhu, Point Chevalier, Ponsonby, Remuera, Richmond (Won by Richmond, 2 pts clear of Remuera, Richmond also won the knockout compeitition)\n*'''Fifth Grade''': Akarana, Athletic, Brown Brothers and Geddes, Devonport, Mount Albert, Richmond (Won by Akarana, 6pts clear of Devonport), (Devonport beat Richmond 15-7 in the knockout final)\n*'''Sixth Grade A''': Akarana, Devonport, Ellerslie, Kingsland, Marist, Newmarket, Northcote, Otahuhu, Richmond, Point Chevalier (Won by Point Chevalier, 6pts clear of Richmond, Richmond won the knockout competition.\n*'''Sixth Grade B''': Akarana, City, Devonport, Marist, Newmarket, Newton, Point Chevalier, Richmond (Won by Point Chevalier, 5 pts clear of Marist, Marist won the knockout competition.\n*'''Primary Schools''': Ellerslie, Mangere, Mount Albert, Newmarket, Newton, Onehunga, Onehunga Convent, Otahuhu, Otahuhu B, Papatoetoe, Richmond (Otahuhu won the final of the school knockout competition after defeating Onehunga Convent 13 to 3).\nRichmond were awarded the Davis\u2019 Points Shield for most junior grade wins. They gained 75 points, with Devonport finishing second.\n\n===Exhibition Matches===\n[[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond]] travelled north to play [[Hikurangi]] in the first rugby league match in the area. The local rugby team had become dissatisfied with their treatment by the rugby union and had switched to the league code. [[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond]] won the match in poor weather by 5 points to 0.\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | List of Exhibition Matches\n|-\n|\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | Venue\n! scope=\"col\" | Attendance\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Exhibition Match\n| 7 July <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Games in the Province/Hikurangi\n| page =12\n| publisher =Auckland Star\n| date = 1928-07-09\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19280709.2.134.8\n| accessdate = 2019-10-03}}</ref>\n|| Hikurangi|| 0 || Richmond || 5 || Hikurangi \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Exhibition Match\n| 8 Aug <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Junior Results\n| page =14\n| publisher =Auckland Star, Volume LIX, Issue 196\n| date = 1928-08-20\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19280820.2.132.3\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n|| Hikurangi|| 13 || Richmond B || 17 || Hikurangi \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Exhibition Match\n| 1 Sep <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Ponsonby V Hikurangi\n| page = 13\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 20041\n| date = 1928-09-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280903.2.135.1\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n|| Hikurangi||10  || Ponsonby ||22  ||Hikurangi \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Exhibition Match\n| 1 Sep <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Ponsonby in the North/Games at Hikurangi\n| page =12\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LIX, Issue 208\n| date = 1928-09-03\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19280903.2.153.6\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n|| Hikurangi Juniors||5  || Ponsonby Juniors ||11  ||Hikurangi \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Exhibition Match\n| 1 Sep <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Ponsonby V Hikurangi\n| page =13\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 20047\n| date = 1928-09-10\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280910.2.132.1\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n|| Ponsonby||17  || Hikurangi ||14  ||Carlaw Park \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Exhibition Match\n| 15 Sep <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Game at Hikurangi\n| page =14\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LIX, Issue 220\n| date = 1928-09-17\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19280917.2.139.1\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n|| Hikurangi||23  || Parnell ||6  ||Hikurangi ||400\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Exhibition Match\n| 6 Oct <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Roope Rooster Final/Marist Defeats Ponsonby/A Margin of Two Points\n| page =14\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 20071\n| date = 1928-10-08\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19281008.2.167.2\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n|| North Auckland||9  || Auckland Selection ||33  ||Whangarei ||1,000\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Exhibition Match\n| 13 Oct <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Hamilton V Northcote\n| page =16\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 20077\n| date = 1928-10-15\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19281015.2.148.1\n| accessdate = 2019-09-29}}</ref>\n|| Northcote ||5  || Hamilton || 3 ||Carlaw Park # 2, 3pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Exhibition Match\n| 20 Oct <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Junior Results\n| page = 14\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 20083\n| date = 1928-10-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19281022.2.153.2\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n|| Mount Albert 3rd Grade ||5  || Huntly Juniors || 15 ||Carlaw Park # 1, 1pm\n|-\n|}\n\n==Representative Fixtures and Trials==\nThe first representative fixture of the season was played against [[Waikato rugby league team|South Auckland]] for the Northern Union Challenge Cup which the visitors had won from [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] in 1927. [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] won the 1928 match by 22 points to 3. The game was played in poor weather and was notable for the number of serious injuries with S. Prentice of [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] breaking his nose, W. Smith of [[Huntly, New Zealand|Huntly]] suffering a severe back injury, and S. Raynor of [[Huntly, New Zealand|Huntly]] breaking his ribs. All three of them were taken to [[Auckland Hospital]].<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Football Accidents\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LIX, Issue 142\n| date = 1928-06-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19280618.2.116.2\n| accessdate = 2019-09-02}}</ref> A midweek trial match was played between the Possibles and Probables in order to select the [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] team which was due to play the touring England side later in the season.\n\n[[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] trounced [[Canterbury rugby league team|Canterbury]] in a Northern Union Cup match by 66 points to 22 with winger S. Hardgrave ([[Newton Rangers|Newton]]) running in five tries. The match was played in good conditions for the most part and was witnessed by an enormous crowd of around 15,000.\n\nA North Island v South Island trial match was played at [[Carlaw Park]]. The North Island team fielded a large contingent of Auckland players including [[Craddock Dufty]], Hardgrave, [[Hec Brisbane]], Wetherill, Prentice, [[Frank Delgrosso]], A. Scott, Hutt, Somers, and J. O\u2019Brien. The North Island team was far too good, winning 44 to 8.\n\nThe following week a Probables v Possibles match was played as part of the selection process for the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] team to play against the touring [[England national rugby league team|England]] side. The two teams featured the following Auckland players (Probables): [[Craddock Dufty]], L. Scott, Brisbane, Seagar, Peckham, [[Wally Somers]], Jim O\u2019Brien, Hall, A. Scott, (Possibles): Beattie, Hanlon, and Cleaver.\n\nThe final match of the season saw [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] go down to [[Waikato rugby league team|South Auckland]] both physically and on the scoreboard by 21 points to 7. The [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] team was below strength.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | 1928 Auckland Representative Fixtures and Trials\n|-\n|\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | Venue\n! scope=\"col\" | Attendance\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Northern Union Challenge Cup\n| 16 June <ref>{{cite news \n| title =A Victory for Auckland/Southern Team Defeated\n| page = 13\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19975\n| date = 1928-06-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280618.2.135.1\n| accessdate = 2019-10-02}}</ref>\n|| Auckland || 22 || South Auckland || 3 || Carlaw Park # 1, 2:45pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Trial Match\n| 11 July <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Trial Match Played/Possibles Beat Probables/Delgrosso a Brilliant Game\n| page = 14\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19996\n| date = 1928-07-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280712.2.168.4\n| accessdate = 2019-09-02}}</ref>\n|| Possibles || 24 || Probables || 14 || Carlaw Park # 1, 2:45pm||1,500\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Northern Union Challenge Cup\n| 21 July <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland and Canterbury/Southern Team Eclipsed/A High Scoring Game/Five Tries to Hardgreave\n| page = 12\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 20005\n| date = 1928-07-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280723.2.124\n| accessdate = 2019-09-02}}</ref>\n|| Auckland || 66 || Canterbury || 26 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3pm||15,000\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Inter Provincial Match\n| 25 July <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Defeat of Auckland/An Exciting Conclusion/Narrow Margin in Fast Game\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 20008\n| date = 1928-07-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280726.2.155\n| accessdate = 2019-10-03}}</ref>\n|| Auckland || 17 || South Auckland || 19 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3pm||2,500\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Inter Island Match\n| 28 July <ref>{{cite news \n| title =North Defeats South/Backs Much Too Clever/Delgrosso in Great Form\n| page = 12\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 20011\n| date = 1928-07-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280730.2.117\n| accessdate = 2019-10-03}}</ref>\n|| North Island || 44 || South Island || 8 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3pm||10,000\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Possibles v Probables Match\n| 1 Aug <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Probables Beat Possibles/Candidates For First Test/Good Performance by Blazey\n| page = 13\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 20014\n| date = 1928-10-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280802.2.129\n| accessdate = 2019-10-03}}</ref>\n|| Probables || 27 || Possibles || 24 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3pm\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | England Tour Match\n| 7 Aug <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Province Beaten/Fourteen Points to Nine/Local Five-Eighths Weak\n| page = 12\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 20020\n| date = 1928-08-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280809.2.118\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n|| Auckland Provincial Team || 9 || England || 14 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3pm||15,000\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | England Tour Match\n| 11 Aug <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Team Beaten/26 Points Against 15/Local Thirteen Tires/Visitors\u2019 Bright Passing\n| page = 12\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 20023\n| date = 1928-08-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280813.2.124\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n|| Auckland || 15 || England || 26 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3pm||25,000\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Northern Union Challenge Cup\n| 15 Sep <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Defeats Otago/Forty-Two Points to 22/Challenge Cup Retained\n| page = 12\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 20053\n| date = 1928-09-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280917.2.125\n| accessdate = 2019-09-02}}</ref>\n|| Auckland || 42 || Otago || 22 || Carlaw Park # 1, 3pm||6,000\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Inter-Provincial Match\n| 15 Oct <ref>{{cite news \n| title = Stormont Shield Contest\n| page = 18\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 20079\n| date = 1928-10-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19281017.2.158.1\n| accessdate = 2019-10-04}}</ref>\n|| South Auckland || 21 || Auckland || 7 || Huntly\n|-\n|}\n\n==Auckland Players Selected for New Zealand==\nThe following Auckland players were selected in the New Zealand team to play the first test versus England at [[Carlaw Park]].\n[[Craddock Dufty|C. Dufty]] (Newton), R. Hardgrave (Newton), C. List (Kingsland), L. Scott (Devonport), M. Wetherill (City), S. Prentice (Richmond), [[Frank Delgrosso|F. Delgrosso]] (Ponsonby), L. Hutt (Ponsonby), W. Somers (Newton), J. O\u2019Brien (Marist), Reserves: T. Peckham (Ponsonby), and T. Hall (Newton). New Zealand won the test by 17 points to 13 in front of 27,000 spectators.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Win for New Zealand/Seventeen to Thirteen/Great Tackling Witnessed/Dominion\u2019s Fine Forwards\n| page = 12\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 20017\n| date = 1928-08-06\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280806.2.107\n| accessdate = 2019-10-03}}</ref>  Brisbane who had not been considered for the first test due to injury was selected for the second test to be played in Dunedin and replaced L. Scott in the side.\n\n==Annual General Meetings and Club News==\nDetails of annual club meetings were as follows, along with notable news during the season.\n*[[Akarana rugby league club|Akarana League Football Club]] held at Carlaw Park. They stated that the 1927 season had been successful with two of their three teams winning their grades.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Akarana Club\n| page = 12\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19900\n| date = 1928-03-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280320.2.141.3\n| accessdate = 2019-09-29}}</ref>\n*[[City Rovers|City Rovers Football Club]] held at Carlaw Park. \n*[[North Shore Albions|Devonport United League Football Club]] held at the Buffalo Lodge Rooms on March 19. During the season Devonport asked the Devonport Domain Board for permission to use the football ground for a match on June 23 and for the authority to charge spectators for entry. Permission was granted provided the charge did not exceed 1 shilling.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Devonport Domain Board\n| page = 16\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19980\n| date = 1928-06-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280623.2.148.2\n| accessdate = 2019-09-10}}</ref>\n*[[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie United League Football Club]] held at their training shed opposite the Ellerslie Railway Station on March 26.\n*[[Glen Eden rugby league team|Glen Eden]] At the Auckland Rugby League's weekly Management Committee meeting in April saw them decide to give financial assistance to the Glen Eden Club toward paying off its ground.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Management Committee/Appointment of Selectors\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19932\n| date = 1928-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280428.2.144.8\n| accessdate = 2019-09-30}}</ref>\n*[[Grafton Athletic|Grafton Athletic Rugby League Football Club]]  held at Leys Institute in Ponsonby.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Grafton Club\u2019s Officers\n| page = 14\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19898\n| date = 1928-03-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280317.2.135.2\n| accessdate = 2019-09-29}}</ref>\n*[[Kingsland Rovers Football Club]] held at Buffalo Lodge Rooms on March 25.\n*[[Mangere United Football Club]] held at Cook's Hall on March 26. During the season W. Hapi the halfback of the Mangere senior team died after a short illness. The Mangere team wore white arm bands on the jerseys for their round 11 match at Carlaw Park against Grafton.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Prominent Player\u2019s Death/W. Hapi, of Mangere/A Clever Native Half-Back\n| page =16 \n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LIX, Issue 168\n| date = 1928-07-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19280718.2.146.2\n| accessdate = 2019-10-03}}</ref> \n*[[Marist Saints|Marist Old Boys]] held at Donovan's Gymnasium in Parnell.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Marist Old Boys\u2019 Club/Annual Meeting Held\n| page = 13\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19896\n| date = 1928-03-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280315.2.155.3\n| accessdate = 2019-09-29}}</ref> \n*[[Mount Albert Lions|Mt Albert]] held their first ever meeting at St George's Hall in Mt Albert. It was decided that they would form a club in Mt Albert though they did no decide on a name at this time. They would enter teams in the third and fourth grades.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Formation of New Club\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19914\n| date = 1928-04-05\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280405.2.152.14\n| accessdate = 2019-09-30}}</ref> During the season Auckland Rugby League made a grant of \u00a33 to Mount Albert for a dressing shed.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Management Committee Meet/Earlier Start of Games/Another Player Reinstated\n| page = 14\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LIX, Issue 139\n| date = 1928-06-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19280614.2.114.3\n| accessdate = 2019-10-02}}</ref>\n*[[New Lynn League Football Club]] held at Foresters\u2019 Hall, New Lynn on March 28.\n*[[Newton Rangers|Newton Rangers Football Club]] held at Nairn's Tea Rooms on Karangahape Road.\n*[[Northcote Tigers|Northcote-Birkenhead Ramblers League Football Club]] held at Foresters\u2019 Hall, Birkenhead on March 22.\n*[[Parnell rugby league club|Parnell League Football Club]] held at Donovan's Gymnasium in Parnell.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Parnell Club\n| page = 14\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19898\n| date = 1928-03-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280317.2.135.2\n| accessdate = 2019-09-29}}</ref> It was noted at the meeting that Parnell had lost its ground as the council was going to put roads through it. They were going to make arrangements to use the Auckland Domain for training purposes.\n*[[Point Chevalier Pirates|Point Chevalier League Football Club]] held in the Point Chevalier Hall.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Akarana Club\n| page = 12\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19900\n| date = 1928-03-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280320.2.141.3\n| accessdate = 2019-09-29}}</ref> \n*[[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United Football Club]] held at The Leys Institute in Ponsonby. Ponsonby were being called \u201cPonies\u201d in the newspapers during the season. Ponsonby played the newly formed Hikurangi during the season and also toured the area with a senior and junior team.\n*[[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond Rovers Football Club]] became the first team to play a rugby league match in Northland when they met the Hikurangi side.\n*Auckland Rugby League Primary Schools\u2019 Management Committee.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Primary Schools\n| page = 14\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19904\n| date = 1928-03-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280324.2.140.9\n| accessdate = 2019-09-29}}</ref> It was stated that eight teams were entered in various competitions in 1927.\n*Junior Management Committee held at Gray's Buildings on March 27.\n*Referees Association held at the League Rooms on March 26. During the season they asked that a written report submitted by its members should suffice for players ordered from the field, rather than requiring them to attend judicial inquiries as it was difficult to attend.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Management Committee Meet/Earlier Start of Games/Another Player Reinstated\n| page = 14\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LIX, Issue 139\n| date = 1928-06-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19280614.2.114.3\n| accessdate = 2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.aucklandleague.co.nz/ Auckland Rugby League Official Site]\n\n[[Category:Auckland Rugby League seasons]]\n[[Category:Rugby league in Auckland]]\n[[Category:Rugby league governing bodies in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Rugby league]]\n", "text_old": "The 1928 [[Auckland Rugby League]] season was its 19th. It was a very busy season, with ten representative fixtures including matches against the touring [[England national rugby league team|England]] team. The senior club season featured over 110 matches through various competitions and did not finish until late October when suburban cricket competitions had already begun.\n\n[[North Shore Albions|Devonport]] won the Senior A Championship for the first time under the [[North Shore Albions|Devonport]] name, though they had won it twice before as [[North Shore Albions]], prior to the merger with Sunnyside. [[Marist Saints|Marist]] won the Roope Rooster Trophy for the first time. This was their first major rugby league trophy and they also went on to defeat Devonport to win the Stormont Shield. [[Grafton Athletic rugby league team|Grafton]] won the Senior B Grade competition with an undefeated season, though they were beaten in the promotion relegation match with [[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie]]. [[Point Chevalier Pirates|Point Chevalier]] defeated [[Grafton Athletic rugby league team|Grafton]] in the Stallard Cup final which was the Senior B knockout competition. The season was notable for the number of teams which played sides from other areas. [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby]], [[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond]], [[Parnell rugby league club|Parnell]], and the [[Northcote Tigers|Northcote and Birkenhead Ramblers]] all played sides from north Auckland and the [[Waikato]].\n\nAt the annual general meeting of [[Auckland Rugby League]] it was noted that out of the 28 playing days during the 1927 season thirteen of them were played in wet weather however crowds were still good and they were happy with the growth of the game. It was also planned for further developments at [[Carlaw Park]] consisting of \u201cconveniences for ladies\u2026extra accommodation\u2026 for players, and three more dressing rooms\u201d at a cost of \u00a360. There was a lengthy discussion about [[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie's]] application to join the A Grade. They had won the B Grade competition and defeated the last placed Grafton from A Grade.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Governing Body/Report on the Past Season\n| page = 17\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19907\n| date = 1928-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280328.2.154\n| accessdate = 2019-09-29}}</ref> The annual general meeting was held at the [[Auckland Chamber of Commerce]] on Swanson Street.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Activities/Mew Officers Elected/Plans for Coming Season\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19920\n| date = 1928-04-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280413.2.165.5\n| accessdate = 2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\nThe Management Committee announced at the midway mark of the senior club season that the Thistle Cup would be awarded to the A or B grade team that had scored the most points in the second round of competition. If two teams were tied then the trophy would be awarded to the team which had scored the most points for the whole season.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Management Committee/Thistle Cup Competition\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19978\n| date = 1928-06-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280621.2.167.4\n| accessdate = 2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\n==Ground Availability==\nAn ongoing issue for many clubs in Auckland was the availability of playing fields as the number of teams grew. During the season [[Northcote Tigers|Northcote]] opened a new field at Stafford Park which is still in existence adjacent to State Highway 1 just north of the [[Auckland Harbour Bridge]]. Devonport also had a deputation present at the [[Devonport Borough Council]] meeting on 10 May to ask about the shortage of grounds in the area. The club asked for permission to use some of the spare cricket grounds for matches. The Mayor, Mr. E. Aldridge said there would be a ground available at Stanley Bay.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Devonport Borough/Shortage of Sports Areas\n| page = 12\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19943\n| date = 1928-05-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280511.2.133\n| accessdate = 2019-10-01}}</ref>\n\n==Rule Changes==\nAfter Round 5 the issue of time keeping in matches at [[Carlaw Park]] was raised at the weekly Management Committee meeting. The bell had been rung in the match between [[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond]] and Devonport at [[Carlaw Park]] before the ball was dead which was against previously arranged rules. Agreement could not be reached on whether the timekeeper or referee should be responsible for calling time. In the end it was decided that official timekeepers should attend the Referees\u2019 Association meeting for instructions.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =The Management Committee/The Calling of Time/Proposed Match for June 4\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LIX, Issue 121\n| date = 1928-05-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19280524.2.126.3\n| accessdate = 2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\nIt was noted that the dead ball area on both fields at [[Carlaw Park]] had been reduced from 12 yards to 8yards in accordance with the laws of Rugby League.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Senior Matches/Individual Scorers\u2019 List/Taylor Leads the Way\n| page = 16\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19971\n| date = 1928-06-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280613.2.177.2\n| accessdate = 2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\nA rule change came into effect during the season after the annual meeting of the [[Rugby Football League|English Rugby League]]. They decided that no forward at any time in the scrum could have both feet off the ground. Also forwards could not drop to one knee to attempt to hook the ball. The game in New Zealand would adhere to these rules.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Amendments to Scrum Laws\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19983\n| date = 1928-06-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280627.2.148.4\n| accessdate = 2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\n{{s-start}}\n        {{s-bef|before=[[1927 Auckland Rugby League season|1927]]}}\n        {{s-ttl|title=19th [[Auckland Rugby League]] season\n        |years=1928}}\n        {{s-aft|after=[[1929 Auckland Rugby League season|1929]]}}\n        {{end}}\n\n==First Grade Championship==\n===Final A Grade Standings===\n{|\n|-\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!width=175 |Team\n!width=20 abbr=\"Played\" |Pld\n!width=20 abbr=\"Won\" |W\n!width=20 abbr=\"Drawn\" |D\n!width=20 abbr=\"Lost\" |L\n!width=20 abbr=\"For\" |F\n!width=20 abbr=\"Against\" |A\n!width=20 abbr=\"Points\" |Pts\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[North Shore Albions|Devonport]]\n|12||9||0||3||224||149||'''18'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond]]\n|12||7||1||4||143||132||'''15'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Newton Rangers|Newton]]\n|12||7||0||5||143||138||'''14'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby]]\n|12||5||2||5||154||144||'''12'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Marist Saints|Marist]]\n|12||5||1||6||154||170||'''11'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[City Rovers]]\n|12||4||0||8||144||164||'''8'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie]]\n|12||3||0||9||102||162||'''6'''\n|-\n|}\n\n===First Grade A Division Fixtures===\nThe opening weekend of the season saw 4 first grade matches played at [[Carlaw Park]], though these matches were not part of the competition. The round was dedicated to Richard Stack (commonly known as Dick Stack) of the [[Newton Rangers]] who had suffered a broken leg in the Stormont Shield final the previous season and the injury was so bad [[Auckland Hospital]] staff were forced to amputate it. This mean that he was unable to continue in his career and so the league fundraised for him to start him in his own business. \u00a3500 was taken at the gates for him. The day also featured a program of boxing matches with the prizes donated back to Stack. After all the accounts were balanced it was worked out that the fund for Stack totalled \u00a3610 12/3.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Stack Benefit/Sum of \u00a3610 for League Football Player/A Pleasing Effort\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LIX, Issue 152\n| date = 1928-06-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19280629.2.15\n| accessdate = 2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nRound 1 saw the newly promoted [[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie]] upset [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby]]. The season was ceremonially kicked off by Miss Peggy Rhodes, daughter of George Rhodes, the chairman of [[Auckland Rugby League]] Management Committee.\n\nFollowing the conclusion of the first ground of Senior A Grade matches ''[[The New Zealand Herald]]'' published for the first time the individual points tallies of all the point scorers. This was the first time this had been done. Taylor of [[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond]] led the standings with 46 points, L. Scott of [[North Shore Albions|Devonport]] had 33, while [[Craddock Dufty|Dufty]] of [[Newton Rangers|Newton]] was third with 26 points.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Senior Matches/Individual Scorers\u2019 List/Taylor Leads the Way\n| page = 16\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19971\n| date = 1928-06-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280613.2.177.2\n| accessdate = 2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\nIt was decided by [[Auckland Rugby League]] after the 3rd round that they would no longer play curtain-raiser matches by Senior A Grade teams at 1:30pm. This was due to players having difficulty getting to the ground on time as they often worked on Saturdays and had to travel from the outer suburbs. A recent example had been the [[Newton Rangers]] v [[North Shore Albions|Devonport]] match where several [[Newton Rangers|Newton]] players had arrived late and the match was so late kicking off that the second half lasted only 25 minutes instead of 40.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =The Stack Benefit Fund/Next Saturday\u2019s Attraction/Devonport and Richmond\n| page = 16\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19947\n| date = 1928-05-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280516.2.171.2\n| accessdate = 2019-10-01}}</ref>\n\nThe Round 6 match between [[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond]] and [[Ellerslie Eagles|Ellerslie]] was played on the Kings Birthday holiday as part of the celebrations.\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | 1928 First Grade Results\n|-\n|\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | Venue\n! scope=\"col\" | Attendance\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Stack Benefit Matches\n| 21 April <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Stack Benefit Matches/Large Crowd at Carlaw Park/An Interesting Day\u2019s Sport\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19928\n| date = 1928-04-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280423.2.149.2\n| accessdate = 2019-09-30}}</ref>\n|| Ponsonby || 13 || Newton || 0 || Carlaw Park # 1||10,000\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | -\n| 21 April || Marist || 3 || Devonport || 0 || Carlaw Park # 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | -\n| 21 April || Richmond || 10 || City || 0 || Carlaw Park # 2\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | -\n| 21 April || Grafton || 2 || Ellerslie || 0 || Carlaw Park # 2\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Round 1\n| 28 April <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Opening of the Season/Two Surprise Results/Ellerslie Beats Ponsonby\n| page =13 \n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXV, Issue 19933\n| date = 1928-03-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19280430.2.152.10\n| accessdate = 2019-09-30}}</ref>\n|| Richmond || 18 ||