 in 1824 as the length of a (theoretical) pendulum that would have a period of {{frac|12|38}}&nbsp;seconds at 45\u00b0 from the equator</ref> Thereafter as for Sweden.\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Warsaw]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Poland\n|rowspan=\"2\"|stopa\n|297.8<ref name=\"PolishLocal\">{{Citation needed|date=October 2011}} \u2013 Information copied from [[:pl:Stopa polska]]</ref>\n|Until 1819\n|-\n|288.0<ref name=Horace/>\n|(From 1819) Polish stopa\n|-\n|[[Lisbon]]\n|Portugal\n|P\u00e9\n|330.0<ref name=DE1851/>\n|(From 1835)<ref group=Notes>Prior to 1835, the p\u00e9 or foot was not used in Portugal \u2013 instead a palm was used.  In 1835 the size of the palm was increased from 217.37&nbsp;mm (according to Palaiseau) to 220&nbsp;mm</ref>\n|-\n|[[South Africa]]\n|South Africa\n|[[Cape foot]]\n|314.858<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.fig.net/pub/cairo/papers/wshs_03/wshs03_02_zakiewich.pdf\n |author      = Tomasz Zakiewicz\n |title       = The Cape Geodetic Standards and Their Impact on Africa\n |publisher   = FIG, Cairo\n |date        = April 2005\n |accessdate  = January 4, 2012\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120120235610/http://www.fig.net/pub/cairo/papers/wshs_03/wshs03_02_zakiewich.pdf\n |archivedate = January 20, 2012\n |df          = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n|Originally equal to the Rijnland foot; redefined as 1.033 English feet in 1859.\n|-\n|[[Burgos]] and [[Castile (historical region)|Castile]]\n|Spain\n|Pie de Burgos/<br>Castellano\n|278.6<ref name=Traite/>\n|(1759) Quoted as \"122.43 lignes\"<ref group=Notes name=lignes/>\n|-\n|[[Toledo, Spain|Toledo]]\n|Spain\n|Pie\n|279.0<ref name=Traite/>\n|(1759) Quoted as \"10 pouces 3.7 lignes\"<ref group=Notes name=lignes>The source document used pre-metric French units (pied, pouce and lignes)</ref>\n|-\n|[[Sweden]]\n|Sweden\n|fot\n|296.9<ref name=Bruhns/>\n|= 12 tum (inches). The Swedish ''fot'' was also used in Finland (''\"jalka\"'').\n|-\n|[[Z\u00fcrich]]\n|Switzerland\n|\n|300.0<ref name=rose/>\n|\n|-\n|[[Galicia (eastern Europe)|Galicia]]\n|Ukraine, Poland\n|stopa galicyjska\n|296.96<ref name=Horace/>\n|Part of Austria before World War I\n|-\n|[[Scotland]]\n|United Kingdom\n|fuit, fit, troigh\n|305.287<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.scan.org.uk/measures/distance.asp\n |title       = Scottish Weights and Measures: Distance and Area\n |publisher   = Scottish Archive Network\n |accessdate  = January 28, 2010\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090814193601/http://www.scan.org.uk/measures/distance.asp\n |archivedate = August 14, 2009\n |df          = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n|<ref group=Notes>The Scots foot ceased to be legal after the [[Acts of Union 1707|Act of Union]] in 1707</ref>\n|}\n(In Belgium, the words ''pied'' (French) and ''voet'' (Dutch) would have been used interchangeably.)\n\n'''Notes'''\n<references group=Notes/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Anthropic units]]\n* [[English units]]\n* [[David Mermin|Mermin's foot]]\n* [[Metric foot]]\n* [[History of measurement]]\n* [[Imperial units]]\n* [[International System of Units]]\n* [[Pous]]\n* [[Systems of measurement]]\n* [[United States customary units]]\n* [[Units of measurement]]\n* [[Korean units of measurement]]\n\n== Notes ==\n<references group = \"Note\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Imperial units}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foot}}\n[[Category:Customary units of measurement in the United States]]\n[[Category:Human-based units of measurement]]\n[[Category:Imperial units]]\n[[Category:Units of length]]\n", "name_user": "Halbared", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foot_(unit)"}
